title: For Sale/Trade:  New vs Used
postcontent:
Wow for every 1 pissed off e-mail I get I receive 5 great posts.
buying online is cheaper, Buds Guns, Kentucky Guns or search slickguns. Finds the best price on the net....  most ship to your FFL for free and your FFL charges a fee. Mine is $20.00 for the transfer. Oh and did I mention no sales tax???? If you live in another state. Be a smart consumer and stop paying new prices for used guns! #:D 

If you have a new firearm that means you are an FFL dealer and it hasn't been transfered. Trying to sell anything for what you paid for it is crazy. I would pay extra and go through an FFL and have a warranty from the manufacturer.... it doesn't matter if you have never fired it it's still used. Let's face it you took it to a gun shop and they were going to give you maybe 50% of new if you were lucky. That's why your here!!!! Please list as new or like new guys and gals..... if you want full value trade and give the other person the same consideration. Work something out realisticly..... This post is not directed at one person, just 60% of you and you know who you are.... I just picked a a manufacturer out of the the blue.

title: For Sale:  $470 CZ 75D PCR in perfect condition, CHEAP!
location: Salt Lake City, Salt Lake City, Utah
postcontent:
This CZ 75D PCR is amazing. It is a light alloy frame de-cocker model featuring an extended magazine release, low profile snag-free sights, and a loaded chamber indicator.

I am selling it because I am leaving the country, and can’t take it with me. It is an amazing firing gun.
It is in almost perfect condition, and have put less than 500 rounds through it. It comes with 2-14 round magazines, 200+ 9mm rounds, and a fabric holster.
Contact me right away!


This gun is NATO certified, meaning that this pistol must be 100% reliable in extreme conditions, the following is a list of some of the minimum requirements.


Must be able to complete the following without failure:


4000 dry firings


3000 De-cockings


Operator level disassembly 1350 times with out ware or damage to components.


Complete disassembly 150 times, this is all the way down, pins, springs etc.


100% interchangability, any number of pistols randomly selected, disassembled, parts mixed and reassembled with no failures of any kind including loss of accuracy.

Safety requirements:


Drop test


1.5 meter (4.9”) drop test, this is done 54 times with the pistol loaded (blank) and the hammer cocked. Dropping the pistol on the butt, the muzzle, back of the slide, sides of the gun, top of the slide, in essence, any angle that you could drop the gun from. This is done on concrete and 0 failures are allowed! A failure is the gun firing.


3meter drop (9.8”) 5 times with the pistol loaded (blank) and the hammer cocked, This is done on concrete and 0 failures are allowed! A failure is the gun firing.


After these tests are complete the gun must fire without service.


The factory contracted an independent lab to do additional testing on guns that previously passed the drop tests.

These pistol were dropped an additional 352 times without failure.


The pistol must also complete an environmental conditions test:


This means cold, heat, dust/sand and mud.


The pistol must fire after being frozen for 24 hours at –35C (-36F).


The pistol must fire after being heated for 24 hours at 70C (126F)


The pistol must fire after being submerged in mud, sand and combinations including being stripped of oil then completing the sand and mud tests again.

Service life:


The service life requirement from the Czech police was 15,000 rounds of +P ammo!


The pistol will exceed 30,000 rounds with ball 9mm.

Reliability:


The reliability requirements for the P-01 pistol are 99.8%, that’s a .2% failure rate.


This equals 20 stoppages in 10,000 rounds or 500 “Mean Rounds Between Failure” (MRBF)


During testing, the average number of stoppages was only 7 per 15,000 rounds fired, this is a .05% failure rate, a MRBF rate of 2142 rounds! Over 4 time the minimum acceptable requirement.


The U.S. Army MRBF requirement is 495 rounds for 9mm pistols with 115 grain Ball ammunition.
